```
class FloatWithUnits
{
    public float value { get; set; }
    public string unit { get; set; }

    public override string ToString()
    {
        return $"{value} {unit}";
    }
}
```
This method takes advantage of the `string.Format` method to concatenate the value and unit with a space in between, resulting in a string representation of the `FloatWithUnits` struct that includes both the value and unit.

For example, if you have a `FloatWithUnits` struct called `myFloat` with values 1.8 and units "meters", it will output "1.8 meters" when you call the `ToString()` method on it.
```
 FloatWithUnits myFloat = new FloatWithUnits { value = 1.8f, unit = "meters" };
 Console.WriteLine(myFloat); // Output: 1.8 meters
```
